    "client_msg_id": "d72411da-baaa-4209-a874-3fd97295eb8d",
    "type": "message",
    "text": "Yeah - great examples <@UA14TGLTC>. I am thinking more metaphorically and less literally (hence the comment about 'philosophical'). There seems to be a similarity that you can express more in less space because the abstractions are the 'dictionary' - so to speak - of the compression. The second point is that it's often closer to *lossy* compression - there are details that just can't be encoded. E.g. if a language provides the 'function' abstraction, you cant decide what lower level mechanism is used to implement it (same with data types, memory management, etc.). The reason I think this is important is because once we accept abstraction is a lossy compression scheme to make the vast possibilities of system behavior fit in our small brains, we'll look for the losses in all our abstractions to understand them better. Also it seems more important to have a better model to cross the abstraction boundaries, than to look for the perfect/good abstractions of programming.",
    "user": "U8A5MS6R1",
